# Terminal Setup

## Local environment

- Shell: fish (built-in autosuggestions + tab completion — no plugins needed)
- History: Atuin (`~/.atuin/bin/atuin`) — visual ctrl-r search
- Prompt: Starship (`/opt/homebrew/bin/starship`)
- Terminal: Ghostty + Catppuccin Mocha

---

## Shell comparison

| Feature | bash | zsh | fish |
|---|---|---|---|
| Built-in autosuggestions (ghost text) | No | No | Yes |
| Tab completion | Yes (needs bash-completion pkg) | Yes, better than bash | Yes, very good |
| Syntax highlighting as you type | No | No | Yes |
| History search ctrl-r | Basic, built-in | Better, built-in | Good, built-in |
| Available on remote Linux by default | Almost always | Sometimes | Rarely |
| Needs plugins for full experience | Yes | Yes | No |

### Key conclusions

- No shell gives you autocomplete on a remote host without something installed there.
  The shell runs on the remote — it must be installed there to work there.
- No shell lets you project a local theme/prompt onto a remote session.
  The remote shell controls what gets printed.
- The only free remote experience is whatever bash already provides on the server
  (tab completion and basic ctrl-r). That costs you nothing because it is already there.

