## Bash on Mac — full setup guide

macOS ships with bash 3.2 (2007, kept for licensing reasons). It is too old for
modern completions. You need to install bash 5.x from Homebrew.

### 1 — Install modern bash

```bash
brew install bash
# Add to allowed shells
echo /opt/homebrew/bin/bash | sudo tee -a /etc/shells
# Switch your default shell (log out and back in after)
chsh -s /opt/homebrew/bin/bash
```

### 2 — Tab completion for everything (not just paths)

bash-completion@2 gives you completions for git branches, docker containers,
ssh hostnames, brew packages, kubectl contexts, and hundreds more.

```bash
brew install bash-completion@2
```

Add to `~/.bash_profile` (not `~/.bashrc` — on Mac, bash_profile is the login file):

```bash
# Homebrew bash completion
[[ -r "/opt/homebrew/etc/profile.d/bash_completion.sh" ]] && \
    source "/opt/homebrew/etc/profile.d/bash_completion.sh"
```

What you get for free after this: git, ssh, curl, tar, make, systemctl, docker,
kubectl, brew, and any other tool that ships completion scripts with Homebrew.

### 3 — Starship prompt (already installed)

Add to `~/.bash_profile`:

```bash
eval "$(starship init bash)"
```

### 4 — Visual history search

**Option A — fzf (lightweight, just fuzzy ctrl-r, nothing else)**

```bash
brew install fzf
$(brew --prefix)/opt/fzf/install   # interactive installer, say yes to key bindings
```

Gives you ctrl-r as a full-screen fuzzy search over your history.
No daemon, no sync, no account — just a better ctrl-r.

**Option B — atuin (already installed locally, richer UI + optional sync)**

Add to `~/.bash_profile`:

```bash
eval "$(atuin init bash)"
```

### Full `~/.bash_profile` example

```bash
# Modern bash completion
[[ -r "/opt/homebrew/etc/profile.d/bash_completion.sh" ]] && \
    source "/opt/homebrew/etc/profile.d/bash_completion.sh"

# Starship prompt
eval "$(starship init bash)"

# History (choose one)
eval "$(atuin init bash)"          # Option B — atuin
# or: $(brew --prefix)/opt/fzf/install adds its own lines for fzf
```

